Description: [recto] Good Shepherd. There is a woodcut, XV C. (in Paris) of the Good Shepherd (W.L. Schreiber), N° 839 (mentioned Hind, Woodcut, I, p. 71; It is characteristic of the very late Bruegel that allegorised and symbolical subjects are treated as everyday scenes without obvious symbolical indications, e.g. Peasant's Dance, Wedding Banquet etc.. This appears also to Good & Bad Shepherds. The Good Shepherd treated in 1565 in allegorical fashion. Later Bad & Good Shepherd as just a scene from Peasant Life (the exception: The Misanthrope); [verso] The idea of good and bad shepherd that occupied B's mind, he invented Boston & Princeton composition, but not as Christ pendants. Bad Shepherd see painting attr. to Cornelis Massys, formerly with Harris. See also Stridbeck graphic. Good Shepherd in background of 'Misanthrope'. For subject see 1) Bruegel engraving, John X, 1-16, of Faithful Shepherd (B.122); 2) Holbein: Dance of Death: Bishop: 'Percutiam pastorem, et dispergentur oves' XXXVI Mar.XIIII, Mark XIV, 27; 'Le pasteur aussi frapperay mitres & crosses renversées. Et lors quand ie l' attrapperay, seront ses brebis dispersées.' \* And Jesus saith unto them, All ye shall be offended because of me this night: for it is written (Zechariah XIII, 7), I will smite the shepherd, and the sheep shall be scattered.'; 3) Bol; 4) Engraving van Cleve (Exod.22, 23; 2 Reg 24; Jer 26; John 10; 5) 'Cornelis Massys' Harris.

			<part_of.title>John X, 11: I am the good shepherd: the good shepherd giveth his life for the sheep. (cf.
